row.item_desc:
&lt;h1&gt;Welcome to Spark&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thank you for using Spark. Go through the left tabs to set up your website.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Documentation and Support&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will most likely find answers to your questions in the &lt;u&gt;PDF documentation&lt;/u&gt; included, or directly within the left tabs &lt;u&gt;next to each option&lt;/u&gt;. Don&#039;t forget to check out the &lt;a href=&quot;http://themeforest.net/item/spark-responsive-onepage-html5-wordpress-theme/faq/2372522&quot;&gt;Spark WordPress FAQ&lt;/a&gt; as well. &lt;em&gt;If you need further assistance with the configuration of your site, please feel free to send me a message via the contact form on my &lt;a href=&quot;http://themeforest.net/user/JoNa&quot;&gt;profile page&lt;/a&gt; – I’ll try my best to reply promptly. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Choose your preferred version&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Default: &lt;em&gt;Contrasted&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Contrasted:&lt;/strong&gt; sections have alternately white and black backgrounds&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Black:&lt;/strong&gt; all sections have a black background&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;White:&lt;/strong&gt; all sections have a white background&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Custom:&lt;/strong&gt; set your own background using the fields below&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Upload a mobile version of your logo.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/br &gt;&lt;em&gt;Expected image size&lt;/em&gt;: 50×50 pixels&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This logo will replace the standard logo when the site is displayed on a mobile device with a small screen resolution.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Design tip&lt;/strong&gt;: Instead of just making your logo smaller, find a way to display only the important part of it, like you would do for the favicon (the small icon showing in the address bar of your browser). You could get rid of the text or display only the first letter if your logo is text-based.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Choose how the top menu is constructed.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Default: &lt;em&gt;auto&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Auto&lt;/strong&gt;: list all sections - &lt;em&gt;recommended&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manual&lt;/strong&gt;: use the WordPress menu builder - &lt;em&gt;required if you want one or more menu items to point to external pages.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Check out the &lt;u&gt;PDF documentation&lt;/u&gt; for step-by-step instructions&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;List all sections of the main landing page.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Example: &lt;em&gt;Home, Features, Prices, Contact&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tip: &lt;em&gt;Use Drag&amp;Drop to reorder your sections.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For each section you must set a page ID to be displayed in that section: &lt;br /&gt;
— &lt;a href=&quot;post-new.php?post_type=page&quot;&gt;Create a page&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
— Get the page ID number (can be seen in the address bar after &quot;&lt;em&gt;post=*&lt;/em&gt;&quot; on edition mode)&lt;br /&gt;
— Come back here and provide a page ID number for each section.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sections without a page ID won&#039;t be displayed.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A note about the top menu&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;em&gt;the default behavior of the top menu is to construct itself according to these sections: it will use the title as the top text and the subtitle as the subtitle, links will be constructed automatically and the order of the menu items will be the same as the sections. You can change this behavior in the Menu tab&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Add images to be displayed on the main slider.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Default image size: 520×280 pixels&lt;br /&gt;
Fullwidth image size: 940×280 pixels&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;em&gt;(see &lt;strong&gt;Slider Width&lt;/strong&gt; option below)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tip: &lt;em&gt;Use Drag&amp;Drop to reorder your slides.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Choose your preferred transition animation between images&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Default: &lt;em&gt;Auto&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &quot;&lt;em&gt;Auto&lt;/em&gt;&quot; mode will automatically select the &lt;em&gt;Slide&lt;/em&gt; animation if the site is seen on a mobile device with 1-to-1 touch-swipe support, or will select the &lt;em&gt;Fade&lt;/em&gt; animation if the site is seen on a desktop browser&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Select &quot;&lt;em&gt;Fade&lt;/em&gt;&quot; or &quot;&lt;em&gt;Slide&lt;/em&gt;&quot; to have the same animation for both desktop and mobile devices&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Choose the desired width for the slider&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Please note that the &quot;Fullwidth&quot; option will make the Welcome text disappear.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Standard image format&lt;/strong&gt;: 520×280 pixels – &lt;em&gt;provides a space for a &quot;Welcome text&quot; on its left side (configurable below).&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fullwidth image format&lt;/strong&gt;: 940×280 pixels – &lt;em&gt;provides a full-width slider but no welcome text.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Enter your main welcome text.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You can use HTML tags like &amp;lt;p&amp;gt; and &amp;lt;a&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example: &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;em&gt;&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;Designed with the latest technologies and most advanced techniques, this one-page website loads lightning-fast!&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Enter the main button text.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;or leave it blank if you don&#039;t want to display a button here. Example: &quot;&lt;em&gt;Check Out The Features&lt;/em&gt;&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This button is displayed right below the welcome text. It&#039;s a simple &amp;lt;a&amp;gt; link with the following CSS classes: &quot;&lt;em&gt;button featured animate&lt;/em&gt;&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you would like to display a similar button anywhere else in your website simply use this shortcode: &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;em&gt;[button featured=1 url=&quot;#features&quot;]Check Out The Features[/button]&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Enter the main button URL.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Example: &quot;&lt;em&gt;#features&lt;/em&gt;&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can use either a full web address (e.g. &lt;em&gt;http://www.google.com/&lt;/em&gt;) or an internal link (e.g. &lt;em&gt;#section-id&lt;/em&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you would like to display a similar button anywhere else in your website simply use this shortcode: &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;em&gt;[button featured=1 url=&quot;#features&quot;]Check Out The Features[/button]&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;Footer&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Choose a page to display in the footer. This allows you to display text, links, images, widgets, and even to use shortcodes and more in the footer. In order to do so, create a regular page and name it &quot;Footer&quot;, that will be your footer&#039;s content. Then simply select your Footer page bellow.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Important note: &lt;em&gt;there is no footer in the main landing-page, only regular WordPress pages will display the footer area. If you want to display your footer in the landing-page as well, simply go to the &quot;&lt;strong&gt;Landing-page Sections&lt;/strong&gt;&quot; tab and add another section for the footer.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Select a page to be displayed in the footer area.&lt;/strong&gt; This only applies for standard WordPress pages.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note: &lt;strong&gt;there is no footer in the main landing-page&lt;/strong&gt;, if you want to display a footer in the landing-page then just go to the &quot;&lt;em&gt;Landing-page Sections&lt;/em&gt;&quot; tab and simply add another section.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;No footer will appear if there is no page selected.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Choose a performance mode&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;em&gt;If the &quot;Speed&quot; mode isn&#039;t working properly simply revert back to the &quot;Default&quot; mode.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Default:&lt;/strong&gt; deliver Javascript and CSS in separate files.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speed:&lt;/strong&gt; deliver minifed, merged, gzipped, server-cached and with client-side caching rules Javascript and CSS.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fun fact: The Speed mode might provide your site a Grade-A performance score at Yahoo! ySlow and a score of 90+ (out of 100) at Google PageSpeed. &lt;em&gt;Please note that in order to make this possible you must avoid using too many images. Also, the use of other plugins might slower the page.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Note:&lt;/strong&gt; Spark Speed Mode is a theme-level optimization, I recommend you to use a solution like &quot;W3 Total Cache&quot; to cover other plugins and mostly for caching the rendered WordPress pages.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;Shortcodes&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use any of the following shortcodes by simply copy/pasting them into any page, post or text widget.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tip: &lt;em&gt;You can put shortcodes even inside shortcodes.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

